# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: complutense-university-of-madrid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university was founded in 1928 in Aarhus, Denmark.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] It comprises five faculties - Arts, Natural Sciences, Technical Sciences, Health, and Business and Social Sciences - and a total of twenty-seven departments.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] It is home to over thirty internationally recognised research centres, including fifteen centres of excellence funded by the Danish National Research Foundation.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university's alumni include Bjarne Stroustrup, the inventor of programming language C++; Queen Margrethe II of Denmark; King Frederik X of Denmark; and Anders Fogh Rasmussen, former prime minister of Denmark and secretary general of NATO.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Nobel Laureate Jens Christian Skou (Chemistry, 1997) conducted his groundbreaking work on the Na/K-ATPase in Aarhus and remained employed at the university until his retirement.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Two other Nobel laureates, namely Trygve Haavelmo (Economics, 1989) and Dale T.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Mortensen (Economics, 2010), were affiliated with the university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Initially, Aarhus University was founded on 11 September 1928 as *Universitetsundervisningen i Jylland* ("University Studies in Jutland") with a budget of 33,000 DKK, and an enrollment of 64 students, which rose to 78 during the first semester.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university was founded as a response to the increasing number of students at the University of Copenhagen after World War I.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Classrooms were rented from the Technical College and the teaching corps consisted of one professor of philosophy and four associate professors of Danish, English, German and French.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Along with the *Universitets-Samvirket* ("University Association") which consisted of representatives of Aarhus' businesses, organisations, and institutions, the municipality of Aarhus had fought since 1921 to have Denmark's next university located in the city.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 1929, the municipality of Aarhus gave the university land with a landscape of rolling hills.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The design of the university buildings and 12 ha campus area was assigned to architects C.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Møller, Kay Fisker and Povl Stegmann, who won the architectural competition in 1931.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Construction of the first buildings began a year later, but the campus was developed in stages and is still under development as of 2017.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Møller Architects has been responsible for the architectural design of Aarhus University in accordance with the original functionalist design key, perhaps best exemplified by the characteristic yellow brick and tile.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The first buildings were finished in 1933 and housed the Departments of Chemistry, Physics and Anatomy.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] These departments later moved to newer buildings at the campus and the original building complex now house Department of Psychology and Department of Political Science.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The construction of the first stage was funded solely by donations which totaled 935,000 Dkr and the buildings covered an area of 4,190m2.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] One of the most generous contributors to the first stage was *De Forenede Teglværker i Aarhus* ("The United Tileworks of Aarhus") led by director K.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] *Forenede Teglværker* decided to donate 1 million yellow bricks and tiles worth c.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] 50,000 Dkr and later decided to extend the donation to all bricks needed.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The inauguration on 11 September 1933, marked the first official use of the name Aarhus University and was celebrated in a tent on campus, attended by King Christian X, Queen Alexandrine, their son Crown Prince Frederik and Prime Minister Stauning together with 1000 invited guests.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] On 23 April 1934, Aarhus University was given permission to hold examinations by the king and on 10 October 1935, Professor Dr. phil.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Ernst Frandsen was appointed the first rector of the university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Shortages of materials and a stressed economy postponed and delayed further development of Aarhus University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 1941, construction of the Main Building (*Hovedbygningen*) commenced, a complex to house the university aula (assembly hall) and canteen among academic and administrative purposes.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Main Building was finished in 1946 and still stands out from the rest of the university campus as somewhat different in its architectural design.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In comparison with the original 4,190m2 floor space of the first buildings, Aarhus University now holds a floor space of 246,000m2 in the University Park alone.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] A series of buildings outside the main campus adds an additional floor space of 59,000m2.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] From 1928, Aarhus University offered courses in languages and philosophy, but the students were unable to finish their studies without going to the University of Copenhagen for their final examinations.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] After negotiations between the faculties in Aarhus and Copenhagen, the king declared on 8 May 1935 that the final university examinations could be held at the Faculty of Philosophy in Copenhagen as well as at the Faculty of Humanities in Aarhus.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] This was the first final examinations Aarhus University was allowed to hold, but on 24 July 1936 the king granted the Faculty of Humanities the right to hold examinations for the magister degree and in 1940 for the PhD.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University had offered courses in basic medical subjects from 1933 and on 10 October 1935 the Faculty of Medicine was formally established.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The establishment of a Faculty of Medicine in Aarhus was met with some opposition from the Faculty of Medicine at the University of Copenhagen.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The professors thought that the state should not establish a new faculty until the shortcomings of the old one had been solved.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In the end, the professors agreed to sign a recommendation for the new faculty as long as improvements to the old one were not delayed.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] By 1953, the Faculty of Medicine had been fully built, complete with lectures, professorship chairs, final exams, research facilities and the hospitals of Aarhus had been expanded to meet the demands of clinical training.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 1992, the Faculty of Medicine merged with the dental school and changed its name to Faculty of Health Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university established its Faculty of Economics and Law in 1936, but when it offered courses in political science and in psychology (1959 and 1968, respectively), the faculty changed its name to the Faculty of Social Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Committee approved and by declaration of the king on 5 November 1937, the faculty could hold examinations in economics and law.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Courses had been offered in theology since 1932 at the Faculty of Humanities, but in 1942 the Faculty of Theology was formally established.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Already on 22 June 1928, Reverend Balslev of Aarhus had proposed that Universitetsundervisningen i Aarhus (not yet university) taught basic courses in theology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Though the proposal was greeted by the management, the Faculty of Theology in Copenhagen pointed out that it would take three full-time teachers of the New Testament, Old Testament and ecclesiastical history, respectively as well as education in Latin, Greek and Hebrew by the Faculty of Humanities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] At this time, Universitetsundervisningen i Aarhus did not have the financial means to meet these criteria so the case was shelved for the time being.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In April 1931, the case reopened, this time by Bishop Skat Hoffmeyer who proposed free teaching in the required subjects.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The management asked the faculty in Copenhagen if this was acceptable, but because the teaching was free, the faculty saw it as tutoring rather than actual teaching and they neither approved or disproved of such an approach though they did not see it as actual university teaching.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The municipality of Aarhus did not aid with funds and the management deemed a request of the state to be futile so they decided to disregard getting the teaching approved and start it anyway under the supervision of Skat Hoffmeyer.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] On 5 September 1932 the Reverend Asmund held the first lecture in theology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] This private education in theology continued until the university could hire its own professors in 1938, and in 1942 Aarhus University could at long last establish the Faculty of Theology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Aarhus New University Hospital shares Masonic architectural elements related to its history of seat of the Danish Order of Freemasons.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 1938, the university management acknowledged it was time to consider an expansion due to lack of space and overcrowding of the auditoriums.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The solution was the Main Building (*Hovedbygningen*), containing both rooms and facilities for new academic areas, as well as housing for the general administration, an assembly hall and a canteen.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The building was to be organized according to a principle of institutes so that teaching and research took place in certain rooms with their own library and study for the professor.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The construction of the building took place during the German occupation of Denmark (1940–45) in World War II, which affected the process in more than one way.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] No state funds had been involved in the construction of the first university building and a second building for physiology, biochemistry, and a high voltage laboratory, but because the Nazis were against civil use of materials and work forces, the state contributed to the main building.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 1943, the Gestapo, Sicherheitsdienst, Geheime Feldpolizei and Abwehr set up their regional headquarters in the five student halls of residence on campus.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Fearing that the same would happen to the new main building, its completion was delayed.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Møller later wrote that for once there was plenty of time to work on the details of the building, like patterned brickwork, acoustic screens and furniture.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Furniture designer Aage Windeleff, designed the furniture specially for the main building, while Børge Mogensen's industrially produced furniture designs are the most commonly used elsewhere on campus.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The presence of the Gestapo in Aarhus led to multiple arrests of Danish resistance fighters and the resistance movement soon realized they needed outside assistance.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] On 31 October 1944, the Royal Air Force bombed the Gestapo's headquarters in residence halls 4 and 5, also killing ten civilian workers.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] 2 Group Bomber Command carried out the bombing by using 25 Mosquito planes.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The air strike on the University of Aarhus took place in a heavily populated area and the campus was surrounded by three hospitals.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] To avoid civilian casualties, the RAF prepared with a model of the campus, shooting at residence halls 4 and 5 with chalk bags.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Møller was in the main building during the air strike but survived and was later dug free from the rubble.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The reconstructed main building opened on 11 September 1946.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University was an independent institution until 1970, but with management representatives from the city council and the organization of Universitets-Samvirket.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Hereafter, the university became a state-run institution under the first University Act.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] With the next University Act in 1992, external organizations were once again represented in the administration and under the 2003 Act, all Danish universities are governed by a nationwide university board.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] This board appoints the rector, deans and heads of departments instead of the students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] It commenced in January 2004 for the first time and in August 2005, a new rector was appointed.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Earlier, in 1994, the university was a scene of a shooting; three people (including the perpetrator) were killed and two more were injured.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University has hosted significant musical events.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Grateful Dead played there on April 16, 1972; the recorded performance was part of the group's Europe '72 tour.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In the 21st century, several higher education institutions have been merged with Aarhus University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 2007, the National Environmental Research Institute (NERI), until then part of the Ministry of Environment and Energy, and the Danish Institute of Agricultural Sciences (DJF), until then part of the Ministry of Agriculture, were merged into AU.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The two institutions initially formed separate faculties, which later merged with the Faculty of Science to form the Faculty of Science and Technology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 2012, Aarhus University's School of Engineering was merged with the university proper, making it Denmark's largest.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] A major reorganisation of the university effective 1 Jan 2011 reorganised departments into four faculties: Arts, Science and Technology, Health, and Business and Social Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] A further reorganisation occurred effective 1 Jan 2020, where Science and Technology was split into two new entities: Faculty of Technical Sciences and Faculty of Natural Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University's main campus is located in central Aarhus, encircling the University Park (*Universitetsparken*).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The campus master plan competition was won in 1931 by the collaborative scheme of Danish architects Kay Fisker, C.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Møller and Povl Stegmann in collaboration with landscape architect Carl Theodor Sørensen.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The design includes a wide variety of buildings in a large area, but each building is constructed of the same yellow brick and roofing tile and with a common design key, providing the whole campus with a unified appearance.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Construction commenced in 1932 and has continued into present times, lately in 1999-2001 (*Søauditorierne*) and 2014-17 (AU Health).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The original main building was one of the first Danish functionalist public buildings and has been included in the Ministry of Culture's canon of Danish architecture; it is acknowledged as one of the twelve most significant architectural works in the cultural history of Denmark.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In a harmonic interplay with the park, the yellow buildings form a campus that has received international recognition for its aesthetic values and it has been protected by law since 1993, in order to conserve its unique design.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Møller Architects have continued as architects of the campus ever since, except the new department of AU Health currently under construction, designed by Cubo.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The park and campus has been expanded throughout the years, in 1957 the old park of Vennelystparken, just south of the university park was included.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Apart from the main campus, Aarhus University has several smaller campuses and departments throughout Aarhus.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] This includes the campus on Fuglsangs Alle in Aarhus V, hosting a large part of Aarhus BSS, and campus Nobelparken, adjacent to the university park and built in 1997–2004 in red brick, also by C.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Archaeology and anthropology takes residence in Moesgård Manor, an old manor house at the new Moesgård Museum.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University also has locations outside of Aarhus.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In the city of Herning, there is a small campus where a few of the university's business, engineering and technology programmes are taught, called the Department of Business Development and Technology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In Copenhagen, part of the Danish School of Education is located at Campus Emdrup.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Børglum Kollegiet, and youth accommodation in Aarhus is administered by the non-profit housing cooperative of Kollegiekontoret or though the public web-platform Ungdomsboliger.dk providing access to student and youth accommodation all across Denmark.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Only the *Parkkollegierne* (full name: *Kollegierne i Universitetsparken*) dormitories are located on campus and run by Aarhus University; other dormitories are located elsewhere, all across the city.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] It is also the only dormitory exclusively for students at Aarhus University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] As required by Danish law, the rector is appointed by the university board.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The rector in turn appoints deans and deans appoint heads of departments.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] There is no faculty senate and faculty is not involved in the appointment of rector, deans, or department heads.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Hence Danish universities has no faculty governance.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] As of 1 October 2021, more than 32,000 students were enrolled in Aarhus University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Each year more than 1000 international exchange students come to Aarhus University to study for one or two terms.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 2009 close to 3000 international students were enrolled in full degree programmes.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University is an international university with a large proportion of students at the post-baccalaureate level: over half of its students are enrolled in master's degree and PhD programmes.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 2011, 59 of the university's 113 Master's degree programmes were taught in English.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Talent development of young researchers has been identified as one of the university's core activities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] This means that highly qualified students have the option of starting their PhD studies before completing their master's degree.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university's doctoral programmes allow talented students to enroll in a combined Master's/PhD programme either right after completing the master's degree (the 5+3 track) or one year into their master's degree programme (the 4+4 track).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Since 2006 the number of PhD students has risen from approximately 1000 to approximately 1700 in 2010.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The International Centre maintains international partnerships and combines a wide range of services for exchange students, international full-degree students, PhDs and visiting scholars.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The International Centre is often the first stop for foreign students at Aarhus University, since the centre offers advice on finding housing and living in Denmark.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Starting in 2011 all summer courses and summer schools offered by Aarhus University for bachelor's, master's and PhD students will be gathered together and expanded to provide more diversity in a new framework: AU Summer University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In the summer of 2011 more than 80 courses were offered within the fields of humanities, theology, social sciences, health sciences, natural sciences, agricultural sciences, business and educational sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Summer courses are open to both Danish and international students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University has seen some deep administrational changes since the turn of the century and now also includes several large sub-departments such as Aarhus BSS, AU Engineering and others.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Each of these sub-departments offers undergraduate or graduate programmes specific to their own field of study.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university offers eight undergraduate and about 60 graduate programmes in English.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Since 1944, Aarhus University owned Cheminova, a chemical manufacturer which, among other controversies, has been selling methyl parathion pesticide to Brazil farmers.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 2009, senior researcher Mette Jensen emailed her colleagues at AU, asking whether they thought Cheminova should stop selling the controversial pesticides.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] For this, the university threatened her with dismissal.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university's Pro-Vice-Chancellor Søren E.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Frandsen denied that the university had made any mistakes or threatened the freedom of speech and academic freedom of its staff.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] On 30 April 2015, Cheminova was sold to the FMC Corporation for DKK 8.5 billion, a controversial issue in itself.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University is home to 15 Centres of Excellence supported by the Danish National Research Foundation and a considerable number of major research centres.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Some of the university's other major research centres include MindLab and iNANO.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] MINDLAB was established with a DKK 120 million grant awarded by the Danish Ministry of Science, Technology and Innovation.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] At MINDLab neuroscientists, psychologists, biologists, statisticians and researchers from other fields work together to understand the brain, its disorders, and its development through physical and social interactions – and vice versa.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Hence, the programme encompasses physics, chemistry, biology, molecular biology, mathematics and computer science.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In 2011 the National Environmental Research Institute of Denmark (NERI) was organisatorically moved from the Danish Ministry of Environment and Energy and merged into AU, under the new name Danish Centre for Environment and Energy (DCE).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] DCE consists of two departments: department of Ecoscience and Department of Environmental Sciences, as well as a common secretariat, all under the Faculty of Technical Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The core obligations of DCE continues to be to provide research based monitoring and advice to the Danish Government on environmental issues and conduct independent research and education within the same fields.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Also in 2011 the Agricultural Research Institute of the Ministry of Agriculture was merged into AU.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] First as a separate faculty for Agricultural Research, later as part of the Faculty of Technical Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The former departments are now organised as Departments of Agroecology, Animal Sciences, and Food Science, together with a common secretariat: Danish Centre for Food and Agriculture (DCA).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The core obligations of DCA is to provide advice and supporting research to the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries, while the departments also engage in independent research and teaching.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Global Rust Reference Center provides testing and investigation services of new and difficult cases of wheat stem rust/black stem rust.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Students from different fields meet in the numerous Friday bars and at various events organized by student organizations.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Friday bars are often organised by students from the different departments who set up a small, local bar in a canteen or classroom where beers and non-alcoholic drinks are served.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university also offers the Student bar (*Studenterbaren*) though Studenterhus Aarhus.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university also has a number of libraries, some of which are open around the clock with student or employee cards.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Almost every department has its own library, but the main library is the State and University Library.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] It has an extensive electronic journal database which students and staff can access either at the library or from home.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University Sports (AUS) is open to all university students and organises a wide range of activities from badminton, to fencing and chess.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The largest student organisations at Aarhus University are the Student Union (*Studenterrådet ved Aarhus Universitet*) and *Studenterlauget*.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Student Union represents the main student body at Aarhus University in many boards and forums, while *Studenterlauget* is a mainly social organisation at School of Business and Social Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Student Union has both student seats on the university board.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Student Union also arranges annual concerts and seminars, and publishes the student magazine *Delfinen* (The Dolphin).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Conservative Students union publishes the student magazine *Critique*.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Liberal Students union publishes the leaflet Minerva.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University offers many activities and services for foreign and Danish students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Several "Friday Bars", clubs organized and crewed by students at the university offer cheap beer and drinks, which has a wide appeal to the student body.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Studenternes Hus (The Students House) was built in 1964 at the central campus to accommodate students organisations, activities, festivities and gatherings.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Among many other things, the buildings are headquarters to the students organisation *Studenterhus Aarhus*, and Aarhus University offers a free membership to all exchange students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Students House is a meeting place for international and Danish students in Aarhus and *Studenterhus Aarhus* organize social and cultural activities throughout the year, ranging from parties and road trips, to language classes and weekly international nights (a popular dinner club).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The Students' House including the Student bar used to be run by the independent Studenterhusfonden, but was taken over by the university itself in 2020.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] AUS is the official sports club of Aarhus University, and is open to all university students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] It is an umbrella organisation consisting of 18 independent member clubs, which host a wide range of activities, from badminton to fencing to chess.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] In addition, AUS also offers independent activities such as indoor soccer tournaments, badminton facilities, and surfing trips.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Dale's Café is a meeting place for international students and the university's PhD students that opened in 2011.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The café offers coffee, sandwiches and a wide selection of beers.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] It has an informal lounge area where students and young researchers can relax while enjoying snacks and beverages.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Like the main building, Dale's Café is named after Aarhus University's 2010 Nobel Laureate in Economic Sciences, Dale T.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Mortensen Building houses the International Centre, the PhD House and the IC Dormitory, which contains 28 dorm rooms and two apartments dedicated to recently arrived international PhD students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Klubben (in English 'the club') is a bar located at the former ASB (Aarhus School of Business), now under the faculty of School of Business and Social Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The bar is open during regular school hours and weekdays, but hosts larger parties during Fridays and in relation to major sports events.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Admittance is usually restricted to students of the School of Business and Social Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Studenterlauget, School of Business and Social Sciences (at the former ASB) is currently the largest student organisation in Denmark.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The organisation has approximately 4,000 members whom they service through nine smaller "business units".
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Studenterlauget has around 300 student employees.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University is highly ranked by international organizations and maintains its own page listing its current rankings.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] It is ranked 71st by the Shanghai Ranking (2021), 89th by National Taiwan University Ranking (2018), 95th by the *U.S.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] News & World Report* (2018), 106th by *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* (2021), and 155th by *QS World University Rankings* (2021).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus University is a member of the Coimbra Group and of the Utrecht Network.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] Aarhus university is also an active member of the University of the Arctic.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] UArctic is an international cooperative network based in the Circumpolar Arctic region, consisting of more than 200 universities, colleges, and other organizations with an interest in promoting education and research in the Arctic region.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The university participates in UArctic's mobility program north2north.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/aarhus-university] The aim of that program is to enable students of member institutions to study in different parts of the North.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Abbot Oliba is considered a key figure in the repopulation of Catalonia based on Roman and Christian culture, and political pacifism and his assemblies of Peace and Truce of God laid the groundwork for one of the first parliaments in Europe.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is one of the three Spanish universities belonging to the Centro de Estudios Universitarios CEU educational group.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It belongs to the Catholic Association of Propagandists, an institution created in 1908 by the Jesuit priest Ángel Ayala.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The main campus of the UAO CEU is the Bellesguard Campus, in the district of Sarrià-Sant Gervasi.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The origin of the current university is in the CDES Abat Oliba, an institution created by Fundación San Pablo-CEU in 1973 in Barcelona.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The center started its activities in January 1974 through an affiliation agreement with the University of Barcelona.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1995 it became known as the Center for Higher Education Abat Oliba and offered degrees in Law, Business Administration and Management, and Economy.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2003, the Parliament of Catalonia recognized Abat Oliba CEU University as a new university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1992 he acquired the complex built by the modernist architect Bernardí Martorell at the behest of the benefactor Francesca Balart, to convert it into its current headquarters, which opened in 1995.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] That same year, coinciding with the refurbishment by the architect Miquel Àngel Armengou, it was renamed the Abat Oliba Higher Education Centre, incorporating university studies in Law, Business Administration and Management and the first cycle of Economics.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Eight years later, in 2003, the Abat Oliba CEU University is recognised by Law 20/2003, of 4 July 2003, of the Parliament of Catalonia.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It thus becomes one of the three Spanish universities belonging to the CEU educational group.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The spring of 2007 saw the birth of the Goliad UAO CEU Awards, prizes given annually by the advertising and communication students of the Abat Oliba CEU University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2012 the institution started an annual conferenced titled UAO CEU International Journalism Week, lasting an entire week (Monday to Friday), and hosting presentations by professionals and scholars of Journalism.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Also in 2012, the Abat Oliba CEU University and the totality of the Catalan universities pledged to defend the Catalan linguistic immersion model and proposed a coordinated access to the Catalan university system.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The university's rectors since then have been: Juan Corona Ramón (2003–2004) José María Alsina Roca (2004–2009); Carlos Pérez del Valle (2009–2017), Eva Perea (2017-2018), Rafael Rodriguez-Ponga y Salamanca (2019-2024) and Arcadi Gual Sala (since 2024).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] They offer undergraduate, master's and postgraduate degrees in the areas of Communication, Law and Political Science, Education, Business and Economics, Humanities and Psychology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2017 Unesco awarded the UAO CEU the Chair of Peace, Solidarity and Intercultural Dialogue, to promote a comprehensive concept of peace.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] 2020 saw the creation of the Antonio de Montserrat Chair of Global Studies and the Jean Monnet Chair on Fiscal Integration in the European Union, financed with European competitive funds from the Erasmus+ call for Jean Monnet activities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] There is also the Labour Observatory, dedicated to current issues in the world of work, and the Institute of Health Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2020, the university joined the European Federation of Catholic Universities and the International Platform for Cooperation and Migration.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is part of the CEU educational group and is one of three CEU Universities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In addition to its research and teaching function, UAO CEU organises cultural and informative activities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] 2007 saw the creation of the annual GoliADs UAO CEU Awards for advertising and communication, awarded by students of Abat Oliba CEU University in Barcelona to advertising agencies and the media.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Since 2013, it has organised the BCN Thinking Challenge, a university marathon of social entrepreneurship created by the university's Entrepreneurship Club.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2015, the Education Talks were created, spaces for innovation in education which are organised in two annual sessions, one session on educational innovation and another on a monographic theme.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2017, the Digital Communication Week was launched.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Two editions have been held: one focused on the role of artificial intelligence and the other on digital transformation.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is held as part of the Official Master’s Degree in Digital Communication and New Technologies.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Other conferences that the UAO CEU organises are the Law and Society Conference and the European Conference of Christian Anthropology and Mental Health Sciences, which were held for the first time in September 2018 and 2019, respectively.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The UAO CEU was the first university to join the ‘Universitats amb cor’ programme of Caritas Internationalis in Barcelona.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is part of the CEU educational group, the private educational institution that allocates most resources in Spain to scholarships and study grants.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the 2009 Spanish universities ranking by the Institute for Industrial and Financial Analysis (IAIF) of the Complutense University of Madrid, the Abat Oliba CEU University ranks 1st among the Catalan private universities in terms of teaching.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In research, the university holds the 3rd position nationwide.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] One of the patrons of the university is the Archbishop of Barcelona, currently Juan José Omella.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] UAO CEU is the highest-ranking private Catalan university in Spain, as accredited by the Institute of Industrial and Financial Analysis (IAIF) of the Complutense University of Madrid.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In Spain, UAO CEU ranks third place, behind only the University of Navarra and the Comillas Pontifical University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the study Via Universitària (2016), by the Jaume Bofill Foundation and the Xarxa Vives d'Universitats 85% of UAO CEU students are satisfied with their studies.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The seventh ranking of universities of the CyD Foundation (2020) highlighted the performance of UAO CEU in the fields of international mobility, international teaching staff, placements in companies in the region, graduation rate and rate of return on degree.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the QS World University Rankings, drawn up by Times Higher Education, CEU universities are among the 500 best in the world and rank sixth among Spanish universities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] UAO CEU has its main campus at the Bellesguard Campus, located around the former summer palace of the House of Barcelona, where King Martin of Aragon, also known as Martin the Humane, died.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1900, part of the plot was segregated so that the architect Antoni Gaudí could build a residence for the industrialist Jaume Figueres, known as Torre Bellesguard.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] On the rest of the land, in 1925, the Oblates of the Most Holy Redeemer promoted a religious community for carrying out social work, built by the architect Bernardí Martorell thanks to the generosity of Francesca Balart.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Martorell, a disciple of Gaudí, designed a church with hyperboloid vaults, which today serves as the Aula Magna / Aula Sacra.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The church and the cloister were fitted out as headquarters for the UAO CEU by the architect Miquel Àngel Armengou in 1992.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2018, refurbishment work was undertaken in the Aula Magna / Aula Sacra, with the installation of an underfloor heating system and new audiovisual equipment.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2019, the new radio, television and photography studios were inaugurated.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The **Abdelmalek Essaâdi University** is a Moroccan public university established in 1989 and headquartered in Tétouan.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is one of the main higher education institutions in northern Morocco.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university comprises 15 institutions, including faculties, schools, and institutes, distributed across the Tanger-Tétouan-Al Hoceïma region as well as in the city of Larache.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It offers programs in several fields, including sciences, law, economics and management, humanities and social sciences, as well as science and technology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In 2016, the university inaugurated a Confucius Institute dedicated to the teaching of Chinese language and culture, becoming the third institute of this type in Morocco.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university was ranked 82nd in the 2016 regional ranking of Arab universities published by U.S.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Abdelmalek Essaâdi University was founded by virtue of Dahir no.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] 177-398 of 16 October 1975 relating to the creation of universities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In addition to the Presidency, the UAE currently has 15 institutions, namely: six schools and nine faculties.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In addition, 2 schools and 6 faculties will soon be opened..
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university includes the following faculties and schools.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The National Schools and the faculty of science and technology deliver a state engineering degree (Diplôme d'Ingénieur d'État).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The other faculties deliver either a bachelor's (licence) or a master's degree.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university's initial and continuing education programs are aimed at all audiences and offer accredited training in many areas.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university prepares training offers according to the Bachelor framework for accreditation and start of application from the start of the 2021–2022 academic year.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The UAE has been able to develop interesting and promising research potential.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Research at UAE is now structured within 5 CEDs, 38 laboratories, 20 groups and 52 research teams accredited by the University Council (CU).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] For its part, research and international cooperation have been defined in the university's development strategy as priorities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is the guarantor of training and research with an international dimension allowing the university to welcome and train foreign students and to offer its students and staff the opportunity of a departure towards other cultures, with a very present African dimension.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university provides students with a web platform providing resources (PDF courses, videos, etc.) for all branches of study.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The Confucius Institute inaugurated in 2016, is the 3rd Confucius Institute in Morocco with the objective of learning the Chinese language.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The result of a partnership between UAE, Jiangxi Normal University of Science and Technology (China), HANBAN and the General Directorate of Confucius Institutes.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Since its inception, 2,308 students have registered for Chinese language and culture courses, including 308 ISITT students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The Career Center was created in 2016 with the aim of offering UAE students training in "Soft-Skills" non-technical skills and facilitating their access to employability after their university studies.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] More than 15,000 students have benefited from its physical services and nearly 200,000 virtual users have registered on the careercenter.ma platform, which has received more than 1,915,000 visits.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The center uses computer-aided design, engineering, manufacturing and materials science technologies to transform a 3D model into a physical object.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The objective is to develop applied research meeting the needs to support regional and national socio-economic development.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] A center created to support all components of the university and instill a spirit of tolerance, multiculturalism, law and duty.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Several associations and clubs active in sport, charity work, art, journalism, innovation and entrepreneurship are present in the various schools and institutions of the university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] There is also a Student Office in all components of the UAE, which oversees the protection of student rights and the transmission of information to the administrative body.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Abdelmalek Essaâdi University has signed agreements with its international counterparts.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is an effective partner of more than 32 universities around the world, and foresees a number of 50 in 2023.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The partnership with the socioeconomic fabric on a multidimensional scale is very present.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ***Academic Ranking of World Universities*** (***ARWU***), also known as the **Shanghai Ranking**, is one of the annual publications of world university rankings.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The league table was originally compiled and issued by Shanghai Jiao Tong University in 2003, making it the first global university ranking with multifarious indicators.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Since 2009, *ARWU* has been published and copyrighted annually by Shanghai Ranking Consultancy, an organization focusing on higher education that is not legally subordinated to any universities or government agencies.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] In 2011, a board of international advisory consisting of scholars and policy researchers was established to provide suggestions.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The publication currently includes global league tables for institutions as a whole and for a selection of individual subjects, alongside independent regional *Greater China Ranking* and *Macedonian HEIs Ranking*.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Altbach named ARWU's 'consistency, clarity of purpose, and transparency' as significant strengths.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] University of Oxford Chancellor Chris Patten has said "the methodology looks fairly solid ... it looks like a pretty good stab at a fair comparison." While ARWU has originated in China, the ranking have been praised for being unbiased towards Asian institutions, especially Chinese institutions.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ranking has been criticised for "relying too much on award factors" thus undermining the importance of quality of instruction and humanities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2007 paper published in the journal *Scientometrics* found that the results from the Shanghai rankings could not be reproduced from raw data using the method described by Liu and Cheng.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2013 paper in the same journal finally showed how the Shanghai ranking results could be reproduced.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Vincke analyse how the ARWU works, using their insights as specialists of Multiple Criteria Decision Making (MCDM).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Their main conclusions are that the criteria used are not relevant; that the aggregation methodology has a number of major problems; and that insufficient attention has been paid to fundamental choices of criteria.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Cheng, think that the quality of universities cannot be precisely measured by mere numbers and any ranking must be controversial.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They suggest that university and college rankings should be used with caution and their methodologies must be understood clearly before reporting or using the results.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] *ARWU* has been criticised by the European Commission as well as some EU member states for "favour[ing] Anglo-Saxon higher education institutions".
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] For instance, *ARWU* is repeatedly criticised in France, where it triggers an annual controversy, focusing on its ill-adapted character to the French academic system and the unreasonable weight given to research often performed decades ago.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] It is also criticised in France for its use as a motivation for merging universities into larger ones.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Several methods for ranking universities were analyzed.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Many scholars proposed developing new methodologies for global university rankings, expressing concerns about bias against universities in the Arab region within current ranking systems.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They emphasized the need to adjust the weighting of indicators to account for overlooked institutional differences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] There are two categories in *ARWU'*s disciplinary rankings: broad subject fields and specific subjects.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The methodology is similar to that adopted in the overall table, including award factors, paper citation, and the number of highly cited scholars.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Considering the development of specific areas, two independent regional league tables with different methodologies were launched – Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China and Best Chinese Universities Ranking.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Best Chinese Universities Ranking was first released in 2015.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China was first released in 2011.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/accademia-di-belle-arti-di-roma] The **Accademia di Belle Arti di Roma** is a public tertiary academy of art in Rome, Italy.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/accademia-di-belle-arti-di-roma] It was founded in the sixteenth century, but the present institution dates from the time of the unification of Italy and the capture of Rome by the Kingdom of Italy in 1870.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/accademia-di-belle-arti-di-roma] The Accademia di Belle Arti of Rome originates from the Accademia di San Luca ("academy of Saint Luke"), an association of painters, sculptors and architects founded in the latter part of the sixteenth century on the initiative of Girolamo Muziano and Federico Zuccari.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/accademia-di-belle-arti-di-roma] The Scuola Libera del Nudo ("free school of the nude") for the teaching of life-drawing, was opened in 1754, and still exists; it offers free courses outside the academic framework of the academy.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/accademia-di-belle-arti-di-roma] The Accademia di Belle Arti di Roma was re-founded following the capture of Rome in 1870, after which Rome became the capital of Italy.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/accademia-di-belle-arti-di-roma] After a petition from 50 artists requested a reform of the institution, which had previously been under Papal authority, all teaching staff were replaced and the academy was effectively nationalised.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/accademia-di-belle-arti-di-roma] The name was at first Regia Accademia di Belle Arti denominata di San Luca, then Istituto di Belle Arti, and then was changed to Accademia di Belle Arti di Roma.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/accademia-di-belle-arti-di-roma] Like other state art academies in Italy, it falls under the Ministero dell'Istruzione, dell'Universita e della Ricerca, the Italian ministry of education and research.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/ad-complutense] Founded in 1991, Complutense increasingly created youth teams over the decade.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/ad-complutense] In May 2020, the club achieved a first-ever promotion to Tercera División.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The **Adam Mickiewicz University** (Polish: *Uniwersytet im.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adama Mickiewicza w Poznaniu*; Latin: *Universitas Studiorum Mickiewicziana Posnaniensis*) is a research university in Poznań, Poland.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Due to its history, the university is traditionally considered among Poland's most reputable institutions of higher learning, this standing equally being reflected in national rankings.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] It traces its origins to 1611, when under the Royal Charter granted by King Sigismund III Vasa, the Jesuit College became the first university in Poznań.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The Poznań Society for the Advancement of Arts and Sciences which played an important role in leading Poznań to its reputation as a chief intellectual centre during the Age of Positivism and partitions of Poland, initiated founding of the university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The inauguration ceremony of the newly founded institution took place on 7 May 1919 that is 308 years after it was formally established by the Polish king and on 400th anniversary of the foundation of the Lubrański Academy which is considered its predecessor.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Its original name was Piast University (Polish: *Wszechnica Piastowska*), which later in 1920 was renamed to University of Poznań (Polish: *Uniwersytet Poznański*).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] During World War II staff and students of the university opened an underground Polish University of the Western Lands (Polish: *Uniwersytet Ziem Zachodnich*).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 1955 University of Poznań adopted a new patron, the 19th-century Polish Romantic poet Adam Mickiewicz, and changed to its current name.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university is organized into six principal academic units—five research schools consisting of twenty faculties and the doctoral school—with campuses throughout the historic Old Town and Morasko.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university employs roughly 4,000 academics, and has more than 40,000 students who study in some 80 disciplines.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] More than half of the student body are women.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The language of instruction is usually Polish, although several degrees are offered in either German or English.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university library is one of Poland's largest, and houses one of Europe's largest Masonic collections, including the 1723 edition of James Anderson's *The Constitutions of the Free-Masons*.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university is currently publishing over 79 research journals, most of them on Pressto publishing platform based on Open Journal System.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adam Mickiewicz University Repository (AMUR) contains over 23,704 records of research publications and is one of the first research repositories in Poland.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adam Mickiewicz University is a member of the European University Association, EUCEN, SGroup European Universities' Network, Compostela Group of Universities and EPICUR.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] On 28 October 1611, when under the Royal Charter granted by King Sigismund III Vasa, the Jesuit College became the first university in Poznań.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] These edicts were later affirmed with charters issued by King John II Casimir in 1650, and King John III Sobieski in 1678, the university in Poznań lasted until 1773.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Based on these charters, the university granted scholar degrees to its members.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The inauguration ceremony of the newly founded took place on 7 May 1919, that is 308 years after it was formally established by the Polish king and the 400th anniversary of the foundation of the Lubrański Academy which is considered its spiritual predecessor.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Its original name was Piast University (Polish: *Wszechnica Piastowska*), which later in 1920, was renamed to the University of Poznań (Polish: *Uniwersytet Poznański*).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 1920, sociologist Florian Znaniecki founded the first Polish department of sociology at the university, one of the first such departments in Europe.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In the same period of the university's history, botanist Józef Paczoski founded the world's first institute of phytosociology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] After the invasion of Poland, Poznań was annexed by Germany and the university was closed by the Nazis in 1939.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] It was reopened as a German university in 1941, which operated until 1944.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Staff and students of the Polish university, some of them expelled by Germans to Warsaw, opened an underground Polish University of the Western Lands (Polish: *Uniwersytet Ziem Zachodnich*), whose classes met in private apartments (see Education in Poland during World War II).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Many of the professors and staff were imprisoned and executed in Fort VII in Poznań, including professor Stanisław Pawłowski (rector in the years 1932–33).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The Polish university reopened, in much smaller form, after the end of World War II.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 1950, the Medical Faculty, including the Dentistry section and the Faculty of Pharmacy, were split off to form a separate institution, now the Poznań University of Medical Sciences.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 1955, the University of Poznań adopted a new patron, the 19th-century Polish Romantic poet Adam Mickiewicz, and changed to its current name.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university's central administrative building is Collegium Minus, on the west side of Adam Mickiewicz Square at the western end of the street Święty Marcin.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Some teaching takes place in Collegium Maius, another of the aforementioned group of buildings (on ul.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Fredry), although this is mainly used by the medical university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Other buildings in the city centre include former communist party headquarters on Święty Marcin, Collegium Novum (used mainly for language teaching) on Al.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Niepodległości, and the university library on ul.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university also uses a number of other buildings in southern and western districts of Poznań.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] However, it is strongly developing its site at Morasko in the north of the city.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] As of 2006, the faculties of physics, mathematics and computer science, biology, geographical and geological science had moved to the new location.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 2015 they were joined by the faculty of history (Collegium Historicum Novum).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The university also has external branches in other towns of western Poland, including Kalisz, Ostrów Wielkopolski and Słubice.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adam Mickiewicz University maintains close cooperation with Viadrina European University, Germany.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The two universities jointly operate the Collegium Polonicum, located just opposite Viadrina on the Polish side of the Oder River.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] University owns a seasonal polar research station located in the Petuniabukta (Petunia Bay), in the Northern part of Billefjord, and central part of Spitsbergen island in the Svalbard archipelago.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] As of 2024, Adam Mickiewicz University owns and operates retreats in three historical palaces in the Wielkopolska region: the Rococo Ciążeń Palace (built in 1768), the Classicist Gułtowy Palace (built in 1786), and the Neo-Renaissance Palace in Obrzycko (built in 1862).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] At the start of the 2008/2009 academic year, the university had 46,817 undergraduates (including about 18,000 on weekend or evening courses), 1308 doctoral students, and 2247 other post-graduate students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The number of undergraduates declined slightly between 2005 and 2008.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] At the end of 2008, the university had a total of 2892 teaching staff, including 257 full professors and 490 associate/assistant professors.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The Adam Mickiewicz University is one of the top Polish universities.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] It was ranked by *Perspektywy* magazine as the third best Polish university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] International rankings such as ARWU and QS University Rankings rank the university as the fourth best Polish higher level institution.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] On the list of the best Emerging Europe and Central Asia universities compiled by QS University Rankings, the Adam Mickiewicz University was placed as 60th.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In 2020, QS World University Ranking by Subject positioned the Adam Mickiewicz University as one of the best higher level institutions among the top 101–150 in Linguistics, 251–300 in English studies, 371 in Arts & Humanities and 551–600 in Physics & Astronomy, Chemistry and Biology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Adam Mickiewicz University's prestige and large class size have enabled it to graduate a large number of distinguished alumni.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Many AMU alumni are leaders and innovators in the business world, as well as prominents in society and the arts.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Its graduates include authors (Kazimiera Iłłakowiczówna, Ryszard Krynicki, Stanisław Barańczak), journalists (Adam Michnik, Max Kolonko), entrepreneurs (Jan Kulczyk, Grażyna Kulczyk); composer Jan A.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Kaczmarek, the recipient of the Academy Award for Best Original Score (2004); theatre practitioner Lech Raczak, film director Filip Bajon and literary critic and a music aficionado, Jerzy Waldorff.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] One of the most notable resistance fighters of the Home Army during Second World War, Jan Nowak-Jeziorański majored in economics in 1936, he worked as an assistant professor at the university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Hanna Suchocka, 5th Prime Minister of Poland, first woman to hold this post in Poland and the 14th woman to be appointed and serve as prime minister in the world, graduated from university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Additionally, Kazimierz Marcinkiewicz, the 12th Prime Minister of Poland and Roman Giertych, the Deputy Prime Minister of Poland and Minister of National Education between 2006 and 2007, are graduates.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Three graduates of the university have served as Marshals of the Sejm and Senate of the Republic of Poland.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Bohdan Winiarski was one of the longest-serving Judges of the International Court of Justice (1946–1967) and between 1961 and 1964 its president.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Three of the school's graduates, including Alfons Klafkowski (1985–1989), Mieczysław Tyczka (1989–1993) and Julia Przyłębska (since 2016), have served as the Presidents of the Constitutional Tribunal of the Republic of Poland.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Three of the current fifteen members of the court graduated from AMU: Julia Przyłębska, Andrzej Zielonacki and Justyn Piskorski.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Additionally, the President of Poland, Andrzej Duda, refused to swear in Roman Hauser, former President of the Supreme Administrative Court of Poland and Krzysztof Ślebzak as the Tribunal's judges.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] In the 1920s the German military began using a 3-rotor Enigma, whose security was increased in 1930 by the addition of a plugboard.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] The Polish Cipher Bureau sought to break it due to the threat that Poland faced from Germany, but its early attempts did not succeed.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Near the beginning of 1929, the Polish Cipher Bureau realized that mathematicians may make good codebreakers; the bureau invited math students at University of Poznań to take a class on cryptology.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] After the class, the Bureau recruited some students to work part-time at a Bureau branch set up in Poznań for the students.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] On 1 September 1932, 27-year-old Polish mathematician Marian Rejewski and two fellow Poznań University mathematics graduates, Henryk Zygalski and Jerzy Różycki, joined the Bureau full-time and moved to Warsaw.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Their first task was to reconstruct a four-letter German naval cipher.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Recipients of honorary doctorates from the university include Marshal Józef Piłsudski, Marshal Ferdinand Foch, Marie Curie, Ignacy Paderewski, Roman Dmowski, Witold Hensel, Ernst Håkon Jahr, Al Gore, J.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Coetzee, Krzysztof Matyjaszewski, Robert Maxwell and Orhan Pamuk, the recipient of the 2006 Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/adam-mickiewicz-university-in-poznań] Wisława Szymborska, recipient of the 1996 Nobel Prize in Literature, received a degree of Honorary Doctor of Letters of Adam Mickiewicz University in 1995, and it's the only honorary doctorate she has ever accepted.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The **Complutense University of Madrid** (Spanish: *Universidad Complutense de Madrid*, **UCM**; Latin: *Universitas Complutensis Matritensis*) is a public research university located in Madrid.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Founded in Alcalá in 1293 (before relocating to Madrid in 1836), it is one of the oldest operating universities in the world.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] It is located on a sprawling campus that occupies the entirety of the Ciudad Universitaria district of Madrid, with annexes in the district of Somosaguas in the neighboring city of Pozuelo de Alarcón.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] It is named after the ancient Roman settlement of Complutum, now an archeological site in Alcalá de Henares, just east of Madrid.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The Complutense is one of the most historically relevant universities in Spain and in the world, and arguably the most intimately entwined with the development of the Spanish state.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Both the Palacio de la Moncloa (the Prime Minister's official residence) and the Spanish Constitutional Court are located directly on the university's campus grounds.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The university has trained numerous Spanish Prime Ministers, EU Commissioners, and NATO Secretaries-General, as well as members of the Spanish Royal House over the centuries.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] By Royal Decree of 1857, the Central University was the first and only institution in Spain authorized to grant doctorate degrees throughout the Spanish Empire, which established it as the "Docta" (the Learned), making it the ultimate intellectual authority in Spain.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] This power was decentralized in the late 20th century, but the Complutense retained much of its historical precedence to the present day.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] It enrolls over 86,000 students, making it the eighth largest non-distance European university by enrollment.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In 1909, the Central University became one of the first universities in the world to grant a doctorate degree to a woman.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] It was renamed as Universidad de Madrid ('University of Madrid') in 1943.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] On 20 May 1293, King Sancho IV of Castile granted the Archbishop of Toledo, Gonzalo Pérez Gudiel, a royal charter to found a **studium generale** (as universities were known at that time), named *El Estudio de Escuelas Generales* in Alcalá de Henares.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] One of its alumni, Cardinal Cisneros, made extensive purchases of land and ordered the construction of many buildings, in what became the first university campus ex-novo in history: The *Civitas Dei*, or *city of God*, named after the work of Augustine of Hippo.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] On 13 April 1499, Cardinal Cisneros secured from Pope Alexander VI a papal bull to expand *Complutense* into a full university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] This papal bull conferred official recognition throughout Christendom to all degrees granted by the university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] It also renamed the institution ****Universitas Complutensis****, after **Complutum**, which was the Latin name of *Alcalá de Henares*, where the university was originally located.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In the 1509–1510 school year, the Complutense University already operated with five major schools: Arts and Philosophy, Theology, Canon Law, Philology and Medicine.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] During the 16th and 17th centuries, Complutense University became one of the greatest centers of academic excellence in the world.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Many of the leading figures in science, arts and politics of that age studied or taught in Complutense's classrooms.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Special colleges were created for students of foreign origin, such as Flemish or Irish (at the Irish College of San Jorge at Alcalá de Henares).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In 1785, Complutense became one of the first universities in the world to grant a doctorate to a female student, María Isidra de Guzmán y de la Cerda.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In comparison, University of Oxford did not accept female scholars until 1920, and the University of Cambridge did not grant a PhD to a female student until 1926.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In 1824, Francisco Tadeo Calomarde further expanded Complutense by merging it with the University of Sigüenza.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] By a royal order of 29 October 1836, Queen Regent Maria Christina suppressed the university in Alcalá and ordered its move to Madrid, where it took the name of Literary University and, in 1851, of Central University (*Universidad Central*).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The Central University awarded Albert Einstein a Doctor of Science degree Honoris Causa on 28 February 1923; this was the first Doctor of Science degree Honoris Causa that Albert Einstein accepted from a European university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In April 1933, Minister for Education and the Arts Fernando de los Ríos, announced that Einstein had agreed to take charge of a professorship in a research institute, which would bear the name *Instituto Albert Einstein*, under the university's School of Science.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] However, as the political situation began to deteriorate throughout Europe, Einstein ended up accepting a similar position at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The university greatly expanded during the 19th century, and its accommodations in central Madrid proved to be increasingly inadequate.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Besides the greater number of students, after its move from Alcalá the university had been based in a number of preexisting, government-acquired properties – mainly aristocratic mansions and royal châteaux from centuries past, abandoned by their owners for more contemporary lodgings.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] This situation changed in 1927, when by royal decree King Alfonso XIII ceded state-held lands in the proximity of the Palace of La Moncloa to establish space for the University of Madrid.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] At the time, this constituted all of the land between the Royal Palace and the Palace of El Pardo, and today it comprises a vast swath of western Madrid referred to as the "Ciudad Universitaria", or University City of Madrid.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] A council appointed by King Alfonso XIII had decided that the new University of Madrid would require the innovative architecture and planning.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] A team of academics was sent on an international expedition to visit the most prestigious universities in Europe and North America, to combine the best of both continents and design the utopian academic setting.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The trip took them to 19 universities in the American northeast, as well as to Paris, Lyon, Oxford, Berlin, Hamburg, and numerous other European cities, all in an effort to discern the best possible building structure.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Indeed, the original buildings, exemplary amongst them the Schools of Medicine, Pharmacy and Odontology, are an homage to structural functionalism and the graceful utilitarianism of the 1920s.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In the 1970s, following the political instability of the regime of Francisco Franco, the University of Madrid was renamed, dividing existing colleges between the Complutense University of Madrid and the Technical University of Madrid.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] When the city of Alcalá de Henares decided to open a university within the older campus buildings, it was named **Universidad de Alcalá de Henares** to clearly distinguish it from the Complutense University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The University of Madrid has played a major role in the political development of Spain since its founding.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Its graduates have been members, at either congressional or ministerial level, in all of the governments of Spain since the Enlightenment, and their positions in the Second Spanish Republic and the post-Franco transition to democracy were particularly notable.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The former first deputy prime minister, María Teresa Fernández de la Vega, and the former president, José María Aznar, are both graduates of the university.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The Complutense University has also played host to some of the most significant figures of the intellectual world, with a long tradition of visiting professors amongst which feature some of the greats of world academia (most notably, Albert Einstein).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] A significant part of the European intelligentsia flocked to its halls during the 1930s, when democratic Spain provided a refuge from the rising terrors of fascism.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The contemporary Complutense University has also counted numerous Nobel Laureates not only among its graduates, but also its faculty members over the years.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Currently, the Complutense University is the largest university in Spain.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The university currently offers nearly 80 possible majors, 230 individual degrees, and 221 doctorate programs.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The university has over 30 libraries, with over 2 million works in print, a particularly rich archive of over 90,000 historical documents, and one of the most extensive film collections in Europe.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Due to its long history in the capital, the Complutense University enjoys great support from Madrid-based institutions, at a local, national and international level.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The School of Communications, meanwhile, enjoys equally good relations with the press (large part of its professors being former reporters, editors, or directors of major Spanish and international newspapers).
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Most recently, Blanca Portillo, Carmen Maura, Lola Dueñas and Yohana Cobo pre-screened Pedro Almodóvar's Volver; past pre-screening visitors have included director Santiago Segura, actor Alejo Sauras, and writer E.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The Faculty of Fine Arts was created in 1978, and now offers first degrees in Fine Arts, Design, and Preservation and Restoration of Artistic Patrimony; as well as postgraduate magister's and doctorate degrees.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Each year, the Madrid Círculo de Bellas Artes extends special invitations to the Complutense students during its series of annual conferences featuring prominent philosophers, sociologists, and psychologists.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Alejandro Amenábar wrote his first film, Tesis, while still attending the Complutense University.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] All the on-campus scenes in the film were shot in the School of Communications, which Amenábar himself had attended, and the building itself serves as major device in the plot.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The Complutense University publishes a bi-monthly newspaper, the *Gaceta Complutense*, and also features a fully operational radio station, Radio Complutense (107.5 FM), which broadcasts for 12 hours daily; both are run from the School of Communications.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] While the university has a select number of registered dormitories, these are located on the fringes of the campus within bordering neighborhoods, and therefore no students truly live on the campus proper.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Due to the costs, and the fact that university-affiliated lodging is not required, the majority of the Complutense's students live independently, either in non-affiliated dormitories or in actual apartments.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] The University of Madrid is home to over 100 student political, social and sports-related groups.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Aerobics, gym, yoga, swimming, tennis, diving, tai chi, and numerous other courses are offered.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In terms of team sports, the Complutense features male and female basketball, football, and volleyball divisions, as well as rugby.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Chess, badminton, golf, judo, karate, table-tennis, and archery teams are also available.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Internal university games are held several times a year, with all of the different schools competing; the Complutense also participates in the regional university games, held each March at the Puerta del Hierro Stadium in Madrid, and selected national competitions.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] All students, professors, staff members, and family of staff members have the right to be evaluated and attended to at the Complutense University Center for Sport and Fitness Medicine.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Besides an extensive series of accords permitting student/professor exchanges and study abroad opportunity with prestigious universities throughout the world, the Complutense University of Madrid currently operates four full-time institutions outside of Spain.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In the Shanghai Ranking, the UCM is ranked among the best 300 worldwide, and among the top 3 Spanish ones.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In the QS World University Ranking, the UCM is the #164 worldwide, #58 in Europe, and #1 in Spain.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] In the Scimago institution rankings, the UCM is #175 worldwide, #79 in research, and #3 in Spain.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Besides, internationally it is in the top 3% overall, in the top 2% in research, and top 3% in social impact.
[src:complutense-university-of-madrid/complutense-university-of-madrid] Over the course of seven centuries, the University of Madrid has provided invaluable contributions in the sciences, fine arts, and political leadership.
